      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why U-Ending Words Matter in Scrabble</h2>
      <p>U-ending words are the ultimate defensive plays. In standard English, almost nothing hooks onto a final U — no common suffixes start with U, and very few letters form valid two-letter combinations after it. When you play BAYOU or BIJOU near a triple-word square, you're effectively locking that area of the board for your sole use on future turns.</p>
      <p>These words also serve as efficient vowel dumps. With four U tiles in the bag and U being the least useful vowel (apart from its Q partnership), U-ending words like TOFU (7 points), TUTU (4 points), and ECRU (6 points) let you shed excess U tiles without wasting a turn on exchanges. BIJOU stands out at 14 points — the J (8 pts) does the heavy lifting while the OU ending creates a sealed position. FICHU (13 points) uses the H (4 pts) and CH combination effectively for a strong play that's also unhookable.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy Tips</h2>
